      <image source="images/Inv1.12(u)sols.jpg" width="50%">
        <description>Solution graph for checkpoint u showing effect of larger sample size</description>
      </image>
      <p>The center has not changed (0.40), nor has the symmetric shape. But the standard deviation has decreased to 0.154.</p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <p><term>Discussion:</term> Even with randomly drawn samples, sampling variability still exists (random sampling errors). Although not every random sample produces the same characteristics as the population, random sampling has the property that the sample statistics do not consistently overestimate the value of the parameter or consistently underestimate the value of the parameter (which is not changing). The means of the above distributions of sample proportions (the statistics) are both very close to 0.41, the population proportion (the parameter). Because the distributions of the sample statistic (as a random variable) are centered at the value of the population parameter, both graphs are considered to demonstrate an unbiased sampling method. With random samples, <m>E(\hat{p}) = \pi</m>, even when sampling from a finite population.</p>

  <p>Notice that in judging bias we are concerned only with the mean of the distribution, not the shape or variability. However, if we do take larger samples (<m>n</m> = 10 rather than <m>n</m> = 5), we improve the precision of our statistics as they will tend to cluster even more tightly around the population proportion. In designing a study, it is critical to first make sure there is no sampling bias (use random sampling), then the sample size (not the number of samples) will determine how close the statistic can be expected to be to the parameter.</p>

  <assemblage>
    <title>Summary</title>
    <p>We have seen two very desirable properties of sample proportions when using random samples from a large population:
    <ul>
      <li><p>The distribution of sample proportions centers at the population proportion (so the sampling method is unbiased).</p></li>
      <li><p>The distribution of sample proportions has less sample-to-sample variability when we increase the sample size (producing increased precision).</p></li>
    </ul>
    </p>
  </assemblage>

  <p>Simple random samples are not as simple as they sound. They require a complete sampling frame and 100% response rate. This can be quite a challenge, especially if you are interested in individuals throughout the country for example. There are other probability sampling methods that are typically unbiased. See this discussion for a brief introduction to cluster sampling, multistage sampling, stratified sampling, and systematic sample. These techniques will come up later in the text and can be much more practical to carry out.</p>

  <subsection xml:id="practice1-12A">
    <title>Practice Problem 1.12A</title>
  
  <p>Suppose that you take many random samples (i.e., thousands) from a population and graph the distribution of the resulting sample statistics.</p>

  <exercise xml:id="practice-1-12a-a" label="PP1.12A.1">
    <title>Centered Distribution</title>
    <statement>
      <p>If the distribution of sample statistics is centered at the value of the population parameter, then is the sampling method unbiased?</p>
    </statement>
    <choices randomize="no">
      <choice correct="yes">
        <statement>
          <p>Yes, definitely</p>
        </statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>Correct! When the distribution is centered at the parameter value, the method is unbiased by definition.</p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement>
          <p>Maybe or maybe not</p>
        </statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>Not quite. If the distribution is centered at the parameter, that's the definition of unbiased.</p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement>
          <p>No, definitely not</p>
        </statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>Incorrect. A distribution centered at the parameter value indicates an unbiased method.</p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
    </choices>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="practice-1-12a-b" label="PP1.12A.2">
    <title>Normal Distribution</title>
    <statement>
      <p>If the distribution of sample statistics appears to be normally distributed, then is the sampling method unbiased?</p>
    </statement>
    <choices randomize="no">
      <choice>
        <statement>
          <p>Yes, definitely</p>
        </statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>Not quite. Normal shape doesn't guarantee the distribution is centered at the parameter.</p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice correct="yes">
        <statement>
          <p>Maybe or maybe not</p>
        </statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>Correct! The shape doesn't tell us about bias - we need to know where it's centered.</p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement>
          <p>No, definitely not</p>
        </statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>Not quite. A normal distribution could be unbiased if centered at the parameter.</p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
    </choices>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="practice-1-12a-c" label="PP1.12A.3">
    <title>Close to Parameter</title>
    <statement>
      <p>If most of the sample statistics are close to the value of the population parameter, then is the sampling method unbiased?</p>
    </statement>
    <choices randomize="no">
      <choice>
        <statement>
          <p>Yes, definitely</p>
        </statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>Not quite. Being close doesn't guarantee the center (mean) equals the parameter.</p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice correct="yes">
        <statement>
          <p>Maybe or maybe not</p>
        </statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>Correct! Small variability doesn't guarantee the method is unbiased - we need to check the center.</p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement>
          <p>No, definitely not</p>
        </statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>Not quite. If the statistics cluster around the parameter, the method could be unbiased.</p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
    </choices>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="practice-1-12a-d" label="PP1.12A.4">
    <title>Sample Size and Bias</title>
    <statement>
      <p>If the sampling method is biased, then will increasing the sample size reduce the bias?</p>
    </statement>
    <choices randomize="no">
      <choice>
        <statement>
          <p>Yes, definitely</p>
        </statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>Incorrect. Increasing sample size reduces variability but doesn't fix bias.</p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement>
          <p>Maybe or maybe not</p>
        </statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>Not quite. Sample size affects precision, not bias.</p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice correct="yes">
        <statement>
          <p>No, definitely not</p>
        </statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>Correct! Increasing sample size doesn't fix a biased sampling method - it just gives more precise biased estimates.</p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
    </choices>
  </exercise>
</subsection>

